    %p With the root *'mār “say”, the initial radical *' is optional in the preterite and imperfect tenses, mandatory in the deverbatives, and absent (quasi-biconsonantal) elsewhere. This means that there are two past tense paradigms, #{t "άμαρ", "'amar"} and #{t "μώρ", "mār"}, both of which are in free variation; the choice of one over the other in a given context seems to be dependent more on prosody than anything else. In other scales, *'mār behaves as a regular triconsonantal root.
