%p 1) These two Scale III forms are historically derived from the root *wčā' by replacing the final radical *' with a reduplicated *č. This sort of reduplication-cum-augmentation was once a common means for dealing with weak root consonants that had a tendency to drop, but is now not productive at all, surviving only in a number of frozen forms such as these. Most references at present list these as belonging to a separate root *wčāč, which from a synchronic perspective makes the most sense.

